knowledge_graph.title: Sandalwood
knowledge_graph.description: Sandalwood is a class of woods from trees in the genus Santalum. The woods are heavy, yellow, and fine-grained, and, unlike many other aromatic woods, they retain their fragrance for decades. Sandalwood oil is extracted from the woods. Sandalwood is often cited as one of the most expensive woods in the world.

related_questions.question: What is sandalwood good for?
related_questions.snippet: Sandalwood has a long history of use in meditation, yoga and worship for its ability to clear the mind. Sandalwood oil is also used in aromatherapy to promote a sense of calm, relieving anxiety and tension.
related_questions.title: Sandalwood Benefits & Uses

related_questions.question: What is sandalwood smell for?
related_questions.snippet: Sandalwood essential oil smells warm and soothing and, when inhaled or applied to the skin, can help calm the nervous system, relieve stress and anxiety and reduce signs of ageing and skin inflammation.
related_questions.title: What Does Sandalwood Smell Like?

related_questions.question: What does the Bible say about sandalwood?
related_questions.snippet: In Scripture, sandalwood is referred to as “aloes” and is called one of the oils of joy and gladness along with frankincense, myrrh and cedarwood. Nicodemus and Joseph of Arimathea brought sandalwood (aloes) and myrrh to bury Jesus, and in today's market, the amount of oils used would be worth an estimated $200,000.
related_questions.title: Bible Oils: 12 Most Revered Oils and Their Historic Uses

related_questions.question: Can sandalwood grow in the USA?
related_questions.snippet: Sandalwood will not thrive in many parts of the US. Sandalwood varieties that are grown in the US typically do best in hardiness zone 10, where temperatures do not drop below 30° F (-1° C) in the winter.

buttons.subtitle: How Does Sandalwood Smell?
buttons.title: What Does Sandalwood Smell Like? And other Facts about this scent
buttons.snippet: Sandalwood is often described as woody, creamy, and warm. Its fragrance is rich, earthy, and distinctive, transporting you to a serene and tranquil setting. Imagine yourself walking through a dense forest, the air filled with the scent of sandalwood.

buttons.subtitle: What Does Sandalwood Symbolize
buttons.title: Sandalwood - Scents Of Wood
buttons.snippet: The sacred scent of Sandalwood has played an essential role in spiritual practices and ceremonies across the world. In Hinduism, the wood is used to create the sacred fire in rituals, while Buddhists incorporate it in meditation and prayer, symbolizing mindfulness and inner peace.

buttons.title: Sandalwood Uses, Benefits & Side Effects - Drugs.com Herbal Database
buttons.snippet: Sandalwood oil has a warm, woody odor and is commonly used as a fragrance in incense, cosmetics, perfumes, and soaps. It also is used as a flavor for foods and beverages. The wood has been valued in carving because of its dense character.

buttons.subtitle: Is Sandalwood Good For Your Skin?
buttons.title: 10 Sandalwood Benefits For Skin- St.Botanica Blog
buttons.snippet: Sandalwood's anti-inflammatory compounds soothe redness, irritation, and swelling, making it a valuable ingredient for calming sensitive or inflamed skin. It can be particularly helpful in reducing the appearance of acne, eczema, and other skin conditions.

buttons.subtitle: Different Types Of Sandalwood
buttons.title: AUSTRALIAN SANDALWOOD - WASP
buttons.snippet: Are there different types of Sandalwood? Of the 15 different species of sandalwood that grow throughout the world, there are 2 main varieties that are traded internationally. These are Santalum spicatum (Australian sandalwood) and Santalum album (Indian sandalwood).
